Short summary

This paper uses Gaia DR3 GSP-Spec medium-resolution spectroscopy to identify a clean sample of solar-twin candidate stars. The authors select stars by matching atmospheric parameters (Teff, log g, [Fe/H]) to the solar values and present sample statistics, typical abundance offsets, and potential applications for Galactic chemical tagging and high-precision differential abundance studies.

Main findings (GPT-extracted)
- Sample: a catalogue of N (~few hundred—see paper) solar-twin candidates from Gaia DR3 GSP-Spec.
- Typical parameter offsets relative to the Sun: ΔTeff ~ few tens K; Δ[Fe/H] ≤ 0.05 dex for the highest-quality subset.
- Authors highlight the utility of the catalog as a large, homogeneous reference sample for differential abundance work and age benchmarking.

Why it matters for the Atlas
- Connects to stellar populations and chemical evolution pages (solar twins are differential benchmarks used to trace small abundance differences across the disk).
- Useful for understanding abundance spread at solar metallicity and refining stellar-parameter scales.

